column29: RFC Assistant  Reset  Hello, how can I help you?  What is the difference between very large, but finite delay and packet loss?  The primary difference between very large, but finite delay and packet loss is that packet loss causes data packets to be lost completely whereas large, but finite delay causes a delay in the transmission of data packets (as stated in [RFC889], [RFC3168], and [RFC5690]). In other words, a large, but finite delay will cause data packets to be sent after a period of time, while packet loss causes data packets to be lost and not sent at all. This can have a significant impact on quality of service, as packet loss can cause a decrease in throughput and cause applications to become unresponsive. In addition, packet loss can cause audio and video signals to become garbled or disrupted (as stated in [RFC6374] and [RFC8088]). It is also important to consider packet delay and jitter, which are related to packet loss and large, but finite delay (as stated in [RFC9062] and [RFC8321]). column28: to securely add a new SEP key to a trust point DNSKEY RRSet, the resolver should start an acceptance timer and remember all the keys that validated the RRSet. If the resolver ever sees the DNSKEY RRSet without the new key but validly signed, it should stop the acceptance process for that key and reset the acceptance timer. The resolver should also not treat the new key as a trust anchor until the hold-down time expires and it has retrieved and validated a DNSKEY RRSet after the hold-down time that contains the new key

column26: An SCTP endpoint should use the ASSOCIATE primitive to initiate an SCTP association with another endpoint. It should also employ a cookie mechanism, as described by Karn and Simpson in [RFC2522], to protect against synchronization attacks. The startup sequence for this process is described in Section 5 of [RFC9260]. If the T1-cookie timer expires, the endpoint must retransmit COOKIE ECHO and restart the T1-cookie timer, repeating up to 'Max.Init.Retransmits' times before aborting the initialization process and reporting the error to the SCTP user. Additionally, in SHUTDOWN-SENT state, the endpoint must acknowledge any received DATA chunks without delay, and in SHUTDOWN-RECEIVED state, the endpoint must not accept new send requests and must transmit or retransmit data and leave the state when all data in queue is transmitted. Finally, in SHUTDOWN-ACK-SENT state, the endpoint must not accept new send requests from its SCTP user. This process is detailed in [RFC2960] and [RFC4960].
column31: According to RFC8994, "ACP point-to-point" interfaces are native interfaces that exist without operator configuration action, such as physical interfaces in physical devices, and are automatically set to "ACP enable" to provide access to additional connectivity. In contrast, "ACP Multi-Access Virtual Interfaces" are non-native interfaces that need to be created and/or configured by the operator. As stated in RFC8994, "ACP enable" should not be set automatically on non-native interfaces, as this could lead to incorrect paths being used by ACP traffic and could have a negative impact on forwarding in the ACP. Additionally, correct forwarding in the ACP would depend on correct data plane forwarding configuration, including QoS, filtering, and other security, on the data plane path across which the tunnel runs.

column25: In the iSCSI protocol, command numbering is managed session-wide and is used to ensure ordered command delivery over multiple connections. It can also be used as a mechanism for command flow control over a session. In addition, command numbers are carried by the iSCSI PDUs as CmdSN (Command Sequence Number) and are allocated with a 32-bit unsigned counter (modulo 2**32). Comparisons and arithmetic on CmdSN use Serial Number Arithmetic as defined in [RFC1982] where SERIAL_BITS = 32, as stated in [RFC3720] and [RFC7143].
column28: According to RFC5011, adding a new SEP key to a trust point DNSKEY RRSet must be done securely by generating a new key pair, creating a DNSKEY record from the key pair, adding the DNSKEY to the RRSet, and signing the DNSKEY RRSet with the existing trust anchor key. After this, the DNSKEY RRSet must be validated at the resolver, and a hold-down time is imposed to mitigate the risk of a compromise of one of the trust point keys (as stated in RFC5011, Section 2.2. Add Hold-Down). Additionally, a mechanism must be implemented to revoke a DNSKEY, which requires knowledge of the private key of the DNSKEY (as stated in RFC5011, Section 2.1. Revocation).

column23: YANG allows the use of conditional augmentation statements to add new data nodes to an existing entry, but only if certain conditions are met. This ensures that old clients do not receive unexpected changes and continue to interoperate with new servers. The "when" statement form of a condition is used in the augment statement. It must not reference external data outside the target data node because the client has no control over this information. Only an "augment" statement that uses the "when" statement form of a condition can be used in this manner. Mandatory objects can only be added if the condition is false, unless explicitly requested by the client.

column29: BOT: As stated in RFC 889 [1], SCTP provides reliable, ordered, and error-checked delivery of stream-oriented data over a transmission path that may be lossy or prone to delay. The difference between very large, but finite delay and packet loss when it comes to SCTP associations is that while packet loss can lead to gaps in the delivered packets and cause errors in reassembly, finite delay does not disrupt the flow of data, but can still affect the reliability and timeliness of the delivery. [1] RFC 889 - Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP) As stated in RFC 9260 [2], SCTP provides congestion control mechanisms that are designed to ensure fair sharing of network resources among competing flows. In contrast, TCP uses a single congestion control algorithm that is optimized for throughput rather than fairness. Therefore, while both TCP and SCTP can experience delay in the delivery of packets, the way they handle congestion can result in different levels of unfairness among competing flows. [2] RFC 9260 - Transport

column55: OAuth facilitates federated authentication in RDAP by allowing a user to use their existing credentials from a trusted identity provider to access RDAP services. Here's how OAuth helps with federated authentication in RDAP:  Single Sign-On (SSO)**: With OAuth, a user can log in to an identity provider (such as Google, Facebook, or a company's internal system) and then access RDAP services without needing to log in again. This provides a seamless and convenient experience for the user.  Authorization**: OAuth allows the identity provider to authorize the user's access to RDAP resources based on the permissions granted to the user. This means that RDAP servers can rely on the identity provider's authentication and authorization mechanisms, streamlining the process and reducing the need for separate user account management.  Trusted Identity Providers**: By leveraging OAuth, RDAP can trust established identity providers, which reduces the need for RDAP servers to manage user credentials and authentication processes. This also means that users can use their existing accounts with trusted identity providers to access RDAP services, enhancing user convenience and security.  Standardized Protocol**: OAuth is a widely adopted and standardized protocol for authorization, making it a robust choice for facilitating federated authentication in RDAP. This standardization helps ensure interoperability and security across different RDAP implementations and identity providers.  In summary, OAuth plays a significant role in enabling federated authentication in RDAP by providing a standardized, secure, and user-friendly mechanism for users to access RDAP services using their existing credentials from trusted identity providers.

column25: n the iSCSI protocol, command numbering is managed session-wide and is used for ordered command delivery over multiple connections. This is done by assigning a Command Sequence Number (CmdSN) to each command sent from an initiator to a target. Comparisons and arithmetic on CmdSN use Serial Number Arithmetic as defined in [RFC1982] where SERIAL_BITS = 32. Status numbering is per connection and is used to enable missing status detection and recovery in the presence of transient or permanent communication errors. As stated in [RFC3720] and [RFC7143], iSCSI NOP-Out/NOP-In PDUs may be utilized to synchronize the command and status ordering counters of the target and initiator.  Source documents: RFC 7143 RFC 3720
column26: According to the SCTP protocol documents [RFC9260], [RFC2960], and [RFC4960], an SCTP endpoint should use the ASSOCIATE primitive to initiate an association. This is stated in Section 5 of all three documents. Additionally, the endpoint should protect itself against synchronization attacks by using a four-way handshake with cookies, similar to the one described by Karn and Simpson in [RFC2522], as stated in RFC9260. The startup sequence is also described in Section 5 of all three documents. When the T1-cookie timer expires, the endpoint should retransmit the COOKIE ECHO and restart the T1-cookie timer up to 'Max.Init.Retransmits' times before aborting the initialization process and reporting the error to the SCTP user, as stated in RFC2960 and RFC4960. Finally, in SHUTDOWN-SENT state, the endpoint should acknowledge any received DATA chunks without delay, while in SHUTDOWN-RECEIVED state, the endpoint should not accept any new send requests from its SCTP user and transmit or retransmit data until all data in queue is transmitted, as stated in RFC2960 and RFC4960. Source documents: RFC 4960 RFC 9260 RFC 2960
column57: A) "A" first sends an INIT chunk to "Z".  In the INIT, "A" must       provide its Verification Tag (Tag_A) in the Initiate Tag field.       Tag_A SHOULD be a random number in the range of 1 to 4294967295       (see 5.3.1 for Tag value selection).  After sending the INIT, "A"       starts the T1-init timer and enters the COOKIE-WAIT state.     B) "Z" shall respond immediately with an INIT ACK chunk.  The       destination IP address of the INIT ACK MUST be set to the source       IP address of the INIT to which this INIT ACK is responding.  In       the response, besides filling in other parameters, "Z" must set       the Verification Tag field to Tag_A, and also provide its own       Verification Tag (Tag_Z) in the Initiate Tag field. C) Upon reception of the INIT ACK from "Z", "A" shall stop the T1-       init timer and leave COOKIE-WAIT state.  "A" shall then send the       State Cookie received in the INIT ACK chunk in a COOKIE ECHO       chunk, start the T1-cookie timer, and enter the COOKIE-ECHOED       state.        Note: The COOKIE ECHO chunk can be bundled with any pending       outbound DATA chunks, but it MUST be the first chunk in the packet       and until the COOKIE ACK is returned the sender MUST NOT send any       other packets to the peer.     D) Upon reception of the COOKIE ECHO chunk, Endpoint "Z" will reply       with a COOKIE ACK chunk after building a TCB and moving to the       ESTABLISHED state.  A COOKIE ACK chunk may be bundled with any       pending DATA chunks (and/or SACK chunks), but the COOKIE ACK chunk       MUST be the first chunk in the packet.        IMPLEMENTATION NOTE: An implementation may choose to send the       Communication Up notification to the SCTP user upon reception of a       valid COOKIE ECHO chunk.     E) Upon reception of the COOKIE ACK, endpoint "A" will move from the       COOKIE-ECHOED state to the ESTABLISHED state, stopping the T1-       cookie timer.  It may also notify its ULP about the successful       establishment of the association with a Communication Up       notification (see Section 10).

column28: o securely add a new SEP key to a trust point DNSKEY RRSet, the zone operator must first generate a new key pair. Next, the operator must create a DNSKEY record from the key pair and set the SEP and Zone Key bits. The DNSKEY record must then be added to the RRSet and signed only with the existing trust anchor key. After the DNSKEY RRSet and signatures have been propagated, resolvers must wait for various timers to go off before the new SEP key is added as a trust anchor for the trust point. As stated in RFC5011, Section 6.1, this process is intended to mitigate the risk of maliciously adding a trust anchor, but not completely solve it.
column31: The main difference between ACP point-to-point and multi-access virtual interfaces is the number of connected points. An ACP point-to-point virtual interface has two connected points, while an ACP multi-access virtual interface has multiple connected points. Furthermore, an ACP point-to-point virtual interface is typically used for one-to-one connections, while an ACP multi-access virtual interface is typically used for one-to-many connections, as stated in RFC8994 [6.13.5.2.1], RFC1793 [information on the Point-to-MultiPoint interface, see [8]], RFC7038 [Point-to-Multipoint interface type [RFC6845]], RFC8014 [4.5. Virtual Access Point (VAP)] and RFC1770 [connections and not point-to-multi-point]. Autoconfiguration of point-to-multipoint interfaces is also discussed in RFC2844

column23: YANG supports conditional augmentation of data nodes through the use of the "augment" statement. This statement is often used with the "when" statement and/or "if-feature" statement to make the augmentation conditional on some portion of the data model. As stated in RFC8407, only a conditional "augment" statement that uses the "when" statement form of a condition can be used. YANG features enabled on the server cannot be controlled by the client, so it is not safe to add mandatory augmenting data nodes based on the "if-feature" statement. The XPath "when" statement condition must not reference data outside of the target data node because the client does not have any control over this external data. An example of this is provided in RFC8407, where it is okay to augment the "interface" entry with "mandatory-leaf" because the augmentation depends on support for "some-new-iftype". The old client does not know about this type, so it would never select this type; therefore, it would not add a mandatory data node.
column24: OAuth [RFC6749] facilitates federated authentication in RDAP by allowing clients to access protected web resources without having to hand out their credentials. Clients are issued access tokens by authorization servers with the permission of the resource owners. Using OAuth, multiple RDAP servers can form a federation, and the clients can access any server in the same federation by providing one credential registered in any server in that federation, as stated in [RFC7481]. Additionally, OAuth is designed for use with HTTP and thus can be used with RDAP, as stated in [RFC7481].

column29: Computer: In terms of network performance measurement, a very large, but finite delay refers to a delay that is larger than typical delays, but still has a definite value. On the other hand, packet loss means that the packet did not reach its destination and is not recoverable. The main difference between these two concepts is that a very large, but finite delay can be detected by the receiver while packet loss cannot.
column59: To securely add a new SEP (Key Signing Key, KSK) to a DNSKEY RRSet, generate the new key, publish it in the DNSKEY RRSet of the domain's zone as a Secure Entry Point, sign the zone with existing keys, and ensure a smooth rollover by notifying relevant parties. Monitor DNSSEC validation, retire the old key after validation, and maintain detailed documentation of the process for security and audit purposes. Continuous monitoring and periodic key rollovers contribute to sustained DNSSEC security.
column62: ACP (AnyConnect Plus) point-to-point virtual interfaces establish dedicated tunnels for individual remote clients, providing isolated connections to the central network. In contrast, ACP multi-access virtual interfaces enable multiple clients to share a common tunnel, offering a more efficient use of resources. The choice between them depends on the specific connectivity needs and design considerations of the network.

column25: The Internet Small Computer System Interface (iSCSI) protocol uses the command numbering system outlined in RFC 1184 to manage and control commands. This numbering system is used to identify commands within the iSCSI Protocol Data Unit (PDU) header. As stated in RFC4085, this command numbering system is used in the iSCSI command and control interface for the service. Furthermore, RFC 1225, 1460, 2355 and 3639 all reference the use of the command numbering system outlined in RFC 1184 for the iSCSI protocol.

column60: What is the difference between delay and packet loss? Network latency is a measurement of round trip time (RTT) for a packet of data, or the number of milliseconds it takes a packet to travel to a destination (server) and back again. When packets of data fail to reach their destination, your network is experiencing packet loss. Packet loss is expressed as a percent.

column26: When initializing an association, an SCTP endpoint should use the ASSOCIATE primitive as stated in RFC 2960, RFC 4960, and RFC 4666. Additionally, the SCTP endpoints should both take the "active" role and use the same SCTP port as client port and server port, as specified in RFC 8841. Upon completion of the initialization process, the SCTP endpoint's association progresses from one state to another in response to various events such as SCTP user primitive calls, reception of control chunks, and some timeout events as stated in RFC 2960. The association is terminated upon an abort or successful shutdown of the SCTP association, as specified in RFC 3331 and RFC 3332.
column28: According to RFC5011, secure addition of a new SEP key to a trust point DNSKEY RRSet requires generating a new key pair, creating a DNSKEY record from the key pair, setting the SEP and Zone Key bits, adding the DNSKEY to the RRSet, signing the DNSKEY RRSet ONLY with the existing trust anchor key, and waiting for various resolvers' timers to go off and for them to retrieve the new DNSKEY RRSet and signatures [RFC5011]. This procedure is necessary to ensure that the key is properly authenticated and can be used as a trust anchor for the DNS hierarchy [RFC5011].

column24: OAuth is an authorization framework that provides a method for users to access protected web resources without having to provide credentials. It allows multiple RDAP servers to form a federation, and clients can access any server in the same federation by providing one credential registered in any server in that federation. This is outlined in [RFC7481] as stated in Section 3.2 “Federated Authentication” which explains that using OAuth, multiple RDAP servers can form a federation and clients can access any server in the same federation by providing one credential registered in any server in that federation. Additionally, RFC7481 notes that OAuth is designed for use with HTTP, making it an ideal choice for RDAP.
column32: According to [RFC8683], when a device connected to an IPv6-only access network queries for a domain name in a signed zone, by means of a recursive name server that supports DNS64, the result may be a synthesized AAAA record. In this case, if the recursive name server is configured to perform DNSSEC validation and has a valid chain of trust to the zone in question, it will cryptographically validate the negative response from the authoritative name server. This is the expected DNS64 behavior, but if the client device performs DNSSEC validation on the AAAA record, it will fail as it is a synthesized record. As stated in [RFC6147], the best possible scenario from a DNSSEC point of view is when the client requests that the DNS64 server perform the DNSSEC validation.

column26: The endpoint MUST retransmit COOKIE ECHO and restart the T1-cookie timer without changing state. This MUST be repeated up to 'Max.Init.Retransmits' times. After that, the endpoint MUST abort the initialization process and report the error to the SCTP user. Additionally, in SHUTDOWN-SENT state, the endpoint MUST acknowledge any received DATA chunks without delay. In SHUTDOWN-RECEIVED state, the endpoint MUST NOT accept any new send requests from its SCTP user. The endpoint MUST transmit or retransmit data and leave this state when all data in queue is transmitted. Finally, in SHUTDOWN-ACK-SENT state, the endpoint MUST NOT accept any new send requests from its SCTP user.

column25: In the iSCSI protocol, command numbering is managed session-wide and is used for ordered command delivery over multiple connections. All commands (initiator-to-target PDUs) in transit from the initiator to the target are numbered. This numbering is carried by the iSCSI PDU as CmdSN (Command Sequence Number). The numbering is a 32-bit unsigned counter (modulo 2**32) as defined in [RFC1982] and comparisons and arithmetic on CmdSN use Serial Number Arithmetic. As stated in [RFC3720] and [RFC7143], command numbering can also be used as a mechanism for command flow control over a session.
column29: According to RFC 5644, packet loss is detected by the receiver only and a packet is lost when the Type-P-One-way-Delay is either undefined or very large. To distinguish between a packet loss and a very large, but finite delay, RFC 7680 suggests using an upper bound, such as the 255-second theoretical upper bound on the lifetimes of IP packets [RFC791], but good engineering, including an understanding of packet lifetimes, is necessary in practice. As stated in RFC 5481, packet loss is separated from long delay by a waiting time threshold which is set according to RFC 2680 and IPPM-Reporting. If the packet arrives at the measurement destination within the waiting time, it has a finite delay and is not considered lost, otherwise it is designated as lost and its delay is undefined. Packet reordering is essentially an extreme form of delay variation which is not affected by PDV results other than to reflect the more extreme variation.
column54: YANG structures data models into modules and submodules.  A module    can import definitions from other external modules and can include    definitions from submodules.  The hierarchy can be augmented,    allowing one module to add data nodes to the hierarchy defined in    another module. column59: Wygenerowanie nowego klucza SEP:  Użyj narzędzi do generowania kluczy DNS, takich jak dnssec-keygen. Upewnij się, że klucz jest odpowiednio długi i zabezpieczony przed atakami typu brute-force. Podpisanie nowego klucza:  Użyj narzędzi DNSSEC, takich jak dnssec-signzone, aby podpisać strefę DNS przy użyciu nowego klucza SEP. Aktualizacja plików DS:  Zaktualizuj pliki DS (Delegation Signer) dla danej strefy DNS, aby uwzględnić informacje o nowym kluczu SEP. DS to rekord przechowywany w strefie nadrzędnej, który zawiera hasz publicznego klucza SEP. Zmiana DNSKEY RRSet:  Dodaj nowy klucz SEP do DNSKEY RRSet dla strefy. Upewnij się, że stara i nowa wersja klucza są dostępne na serwerze. Rozpowszechnianie nowego klucza:  Zaktualizuj serwery DNS obsługujące daną strefę, aby używały nowego klucza SEP. To może obejmować aktualizację serwerów DNS dla domeny oraz informowanie operatorów innych serwerów DNS o zmianie. Monitorowanie zmian:  Monitoruj logi i raporty związane z DNSSEC, aby sprawdzić, czy proces przebiega zgodnie z oczekiwaniami. Backup kluczy:  Przed wprowadzeniem zmian zrób kopię zapasową kluczy. To pozwoli na przywrócenie poprzedniego stanu w przypadku problemów. Testowanie:  Przeprowadź testy, aby upewnić się, że nowy klucz jest poprawnie skonfigurowany i działa poprawnie. To może obejmować testy z wykorzystaniem narzędzi do weryfikacji DNSSEC, takich jak dig z odpowiednimi flagami. Komunikacja z innymi operatorami DNS:  W razie potrzeby poinformuj innych operatorów DNS o zmianie klucza SEP, szczególnie jeśli istnieje współpraca z innymi domenami lub usługami. Dokumentacja:
